'''Forzan Assan Ouédraogo''' (born 9 May 2006) is a German professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Bundesliga]] club [[RB Leipzig]] and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].

==Club career==

=== Schalke 04 ===
Born in [[Mülheim]] to Burkinabè parents, Ouédraogo began his career with TuS Union 09 Mülheim, spending three years before a move to [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waz.de/sport/fussball/s04/schalke-top-talent-ouedraogo-gut-genug-fuer-die-profis-id238574491.html|title=Schalke: Top-Talent Ouedraogo - gut genug für die Profis?|trans-title=Schalke: Top talent Ouedraogo - good enough for the pros?|first=Andreas|last=Ernst|date=3 June 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=waz.de|language=de|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He signed a contract extension in November 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/personal/foerdervertrag-assan-ouedraogo/|title=Schalke 04 bindet Offensiv-Talent Assan Ouédraogo langfristig|trans-title=Schalke 04 binds attacking talent Assan Ouédraogo in the long term|date=9 November 2022|access-date=28 July 2023|website=schalke04.de|language=de}}</ref> Ahead of the 2023–24 season, he was promoted to the first team, scoring his first goal in a 2–2 away [[Exhibition game|friendly]] draw with [[1. FC Bocholt]] on 6 July, also getting the assist for [[Simon Terodde]]'s goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lomazoma.com/fc-schalke-04-fans-feiern-den-youngster-nach-einem-testspiel/|title=FC Schalke 04: Fans feiern den Youngster nach einem Testspiel|trans-title=FC Schalke 04: Fans celebrate the youngster after a friendly|date=6 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=lomazoma.com|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/sport/fussball/zweite-bundesliga/testspiel-bocholt-schalke-100.html|title=Schalke kommt in Bocholt nicht über Remis hinaus|trans-title=Schalke cannot get beyond a draw in Bocholt|date=6 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=wdr.de|language=de}}</ref> He scored in another friendly game as Schalke 04 beat Polish opposition [[Górnik Zabrze]] 5–0 on 15 July, and these pre-season performances saw him touted as a player with a lot of potential.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/en/friendly-en/zabrze-report-2324/|title=5-0 win over Gornik Zabrze in Mittersill|accessdate=28 July 2023|website=schalke04.de}}</ref><ref name="to">{{cite web|url=https://www.t-online.de/region/essen/lokalsport/id_100213046/fc-schalke-04-ouedraogo-als-hoffnungstraeger.html|title=Ein Mega-Talent als königsblauer Hoffnungsträger|trans-title=A mega talent as a royal blue beacon of hope|date=24 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=t-online.de|language=de}}</ref>

Ouédraogo marked his professional debut in the [[2. Bundesliga]] with a goal; being named as a surprise starter in the away game against [[Hamburger SV]], he received the ball in the penalty area from teammate Simon Terodde, he cut onto his right foot, beating a Hamburger SV defender in the process, before placing the ball beyond goalkeeper [[Daniel Heuer Fernandes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waz.de/sport/fussball/s04/darum-setzt-schalke-trainer-reis-in-hamburg-auf-ouedraogo-id239057073.html|title=Tor gegen den HSV: Assan Ouedraogo knackt Schalke-Rekord|trans-title=Goal against HSV: Assan Ouedraogo breaks the Schalke record|date=28 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=waz.de|language=de}}</ref> Despite his team losing 5–3, his first half goal earned him a spot in Schalke 04 history, as he beat [[Julian Draxler]]'s record as Schalke's youngest goal-scorer in official matches. He also is the youngest player ever of Schalke 04 in competitive and professional matches with an age of 17 years and 80 days, beating [[Volker Abramczik]]'s record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sport1.de/news/fussball/2-bundesliga/2023/07/2-bundesliga-schalke-teenie-assan-ouedraogo-bricht-gegen-hsv-rekorde-von-abramczik-und-draxler|title=S04-Teenie bricht Legenden-Rekord|trans-title=S04 teenager breaks legend's record|date=28 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=sport1.de|language=de}}</ref> Following the game, manager [[Thomas Reis]] said of Ouédraogo: "it was important that we carefully integrated him into training", also stating that he would give him a "necessary break" and "ground him if [he has] to", highlighting that he did not want to rush Ouédraogo's progress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ruhr24.de/s04/fc-schalke-04-assan-ouedraogo-thomas-reis-training-einsatz-zweite-liga-s04-hsv-hamburger-sv-92426039.html|title=Schalke 04 will Ouedraogo behutsam aufbauen: Auf Höhenflug folgen Schmerzen|trans-title=Schalke 04 wants to build up Ouedraogo carefully: Pain follows the flight|first=Marcel|last=Witte|date=28 July 2023|access-date=28 July 2023|website=ruhr24.de|language=de}}</ref>

=== RB Leipzig ===
On 13 June 2024, Ouédraogo moved to [[RB Leipzig]] for a reported fee of €10 million, signing a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://schalke04.de/en/team/ouedraogo-leipzig-transfer/|title=Assan Ouédraogo moves to RB Leipzig|website=FC Schalke 04|date=13 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rbleipzig.com/en/news/2023-2024/assan-ouedraogo-rb-leipzig-schalke-04-transfer-transfer-newsigning/|title=Exceptional talent Assan Ouedraogo moves to RB Leipzig!|website=RB Leipzig|date=13 June 2024}}</ref> He rejected a move to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], and subsequently stated that he made the decision for his development, claiming that young players make biggest strides at RB Leipzig.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Laushway |first=Jack |date=2024-07-18 |title=Assan Ouédraogo explains why he rejected Bayern Munich |url=https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2024/7/18/24200598/assan-ouedraogo-explains-why-he-rejected-bayern-munich-fc-bayern-transfer-rumors-eberl-bundesliga |access-date=2024-09-12 |website=Bavarian Football Works |language=en}}</ref> On 20 September 2025, he scored his first goal for the club in a 3–1 win over [[1.FC Köln|FC Köln]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rbleipzig.com/en/news/assan-ouedraogo-rb-leipzig-first-start-first-goal-1-fc-koln |title=First RBL start, first goal for Assan Ouedraogo |publisher=RB Leipzig |date=23 September 2025 }}</ref> He continued impressing during the [[2025–26 RB Leipzig season|2025–26 season]], earning praise from head coach [[Ole Werner]] and Leipzig star man [[Christoph Baumgartner]] for his development and hard work; these comments came against the backdrop of a game-winning goal from long range against [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-24 |title=RB Leipzig celebrate Assan Ouédraogo's (19) "perfect week" - Get German Football News |url=https://www.getfootballnewsgermany.com/2025/rb-leipzig-celebrate-assan-ouedraogos-19-perfect-week/ |access-date=2026-06-06 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hochrainer |first=Sebastian |title=Bremen besiegt: Ouedraogo zaubert Leipzig zum Bayern-Verfolger |url=https://www.sportschau.de/fussball/bundesliga/ouedraogo-zaubert-leipzig-zum-bayern-verfolger,spielbericht-rb-leipzig-werder-bremen-104.html |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=sportschau.de |language=de}}</ref> During the same match, Ouédraogo suffered a knee injury which forced him to miss the entire month of December.<ref>{{Cite web |last=sportschau.de |title=Sehnenverletzung: Nationalspieler Ouédraogo fehlt RB Leipzig wochenlang |url=https://www.sportschau.de/regional/mdr/mdr-nationalspieler-oudraogo-fehlt-rb-leipzig-wochenlang-100.html |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=sportschau.de |language=de}}</ref> During his January return against [[SC Freiburg]], Ouédraogo again injured his left knee, necessitating a two-month-long recovery.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ouedraogo fehlt Leipzig bis Ende März |url=https://www.kicker.de/ouedraogo-fehlt-leipzig-bis-ende-maerz-1186090/artikel |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=kicker |language=de-DE}}</ref> Ouédraogo returned to the pitch as a substitute on 4 April 2026 against Bremen. He scored once during the season's second half, netting a consolation goal in a 1–4 loss versus Freiburg.<ref>{{Cite web |last=sportschau.de |title=Fußball {{!}} Bundesliga: RB beendet Saison mit derber Pleite in Freiburg |url=https://www.sportschau.de/regional/mdr/mdr-rb-beendet-saison-mit-derber-pleite-in-freiburg-100.html |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=sportschau.de |language=de}}</ref> Compared to Leipzig's other regular starters during the season, Ouédraogo averaged the highest number of points per match.<ref>{{Cite web |title=RB Leipzig Stats, Bundesliga |url=https://fbref.com/en/squads/acbb6a5b/2025-2026/c20/RB-Leipzig-Stats-Bundesliga |access-date=2026-06-06 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Ouédraogo has represented Germany at under-16 and under-17 level.<ref>{{DFB|403404}}</ref> At the [[2023 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], he scored the winning penalty as Germany beat [[France national under-17 football team|France]] 5–4 in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] victory in the final.<ref name=U17EC>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/news/0282-182989bb7eb4-4fac0025443c-1000--germany-take-title-with-shoot-out-win-over-france/|title=Germany take title with shoot-out win over France|date=2 June 2023|website=[[UEFA]]}}</ref> His parents are from Burkina Faso.<ref name=to/> On 1 November 2023, Ouédraogo was called up to the [[2023 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] held in Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/u-17-junioren/news-detail-u-17/wueck-nominiert-den-kader-fuer-fifa-u-17-wm-256324/|title=Wück nominiert den Kader für FIFA U 17-WM|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|trans-title=Wück Nominates the Squad For the FIFA U17 World Cup|language=de|date=1 November 2023|accessdate=10 November 2023|archive-date=3 November 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231103220818/https://www.dfb.de/u-17-junioren/news-detail-u-17/wueck-nominiert-den-kader-fuer-fifa-u-17-wm-256324/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In November 2025, he received his first [[Germany national football team|senior]] call-up from head coach [[Julian Nagelsmann]] after [[Nadiem Amiri]] was sidelined with an injury, ahead of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportschau.de/fussball/nationalmannschaft/dfb-kader-ouedraogo-ersetzt-amiri,dfb-kader-126.html |title=DFB-Kader - Ouédraogo ersetzt Amiri |publisher=Sportschau |language=de |date=10 November 2025 }}</ref> On 17 November, he made his debut in a 6–0 victory over [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], scoring just 102 seconds after coming on.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.zdfheute.de/sport/fussball-wm-qualifikation-deutschland-slowakei-2025-wm-2026-tore-ergebnis-100.html |title=DFB-Elf begeistert und fährt zur WM 2026 |publisher=ZDFheute |language=de |date=17 November 2025 }}</ref>

On 5 June 2026, Ouédraogo was called up to Germany's squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] as a replacement for the injured [[Lennart Karl]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/de/bundesliga/news/lennart-karl-verletzung-assan-ouedraogo-nachnominiert-dfb-wm-26-37720 |title=Im WM-Kader: Ouédraogo ersetzt verletzten Karl! |publisher=Bundesliga |language=de |date=5 June 2026 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
A box-to-box midfielder, Ouédraogo is capable of using both feet, and is lauded for his speed, dribbling, creativity and goal-scoring ability.<ref name=to/> Ouédraogo can play any position in midfield, possessing dynamism which can often lead to the creation of dangerous goalscoring situations.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-13 |title=Exceptional talent Assan Ouedraogo moves to RB Leipzig! |url=https://rbleipzig.com/en/news/2023-2024/assan-ouedraogo-rb-leipzig-schalke-04-transfer-transfer-newsigning/ |access-date=2024-09-12 |website=rbleipzig.com |language=de}}</ref> Due to his height, physicality, technique in tight spaces, and ability to carry the ball forward, Ouédraogo has been likened to players such as [[Paul Pogba]], [[Ryan Gravenberch]] and [[Khéphren Thuram|Khépren Thuram]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Assan Ouédraogo: Schalke’s Record-Breaking Teenage Talent |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/assan-ouedraogo-schalkes-record-breaking-teenage-talent/ |access-date=2024-09-12 |website=Breaking The Lines |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ouédraogo's father is former Burkina Faso international footballer [[Alassane Ouédraogo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://burkina24.com/2022/07/16/forzan-ouedraogo-la-pepite-de-schalke-04/|title=Forzan Ouédraogo, la pépite de Schalke 04|trans-title=Forzan Ouédraogo, the nugget of Schalke 04|date=16 July 2022|access-date=28 July 2023|website=burkina24.com|language=fr}}</ref> Ouédraogo is Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web |last=RBLive |title=Essen verschlafen: Erster Ramadan allein seit Wechsel zu RB Leipzig |url=https://rblive.de/news/rb-leipzigs-assan-ouedraogo-ueber-ramadan-verletzung-und-comeback-4030219 |access-date=2025-11-10 |website=rblive.de |language=de}}</ref>

